Thursday, Jeb. 2, 1933.
Doar sut Dils-
We have been passing along the Aelutian Island all day. The islands run
from Alaska over to a point very near the Siberian coast. They are owned by the
United States and judring by what we saw of them today no other nation is ver
likely to try to take them away from us. Great snow covered rocks rise out of
the Pacific apparently almost
straight up,
and from what t he various ship off-
icers say, entirely uninhabited. They were beautiful in the sunshine of this
- some of the highest I would guess rising 1500 feet above the sea.
We ran within twenty or thirty miles of t hem.
Tonight we cross the 180th meridian, and so tomorrow will be Saturday,
instead of Friday. The weather has been very much better since Monday
night,
and the crew all say that this has been to
date a very smooth crossing for this
time of the year. It is very cold out and just now especially as the wind is
from the Northwest,
blowing at a velosity of forty miles an hour, and coming
from across Siberta which as I guess you know is not a rival of Miami for the
winter season.
Groger and I had a Chinese dinner Monday ni ght, chop sticks and all.
We started with "bird's nest"
soup, then dried duck which was terrible,
a lot of side dishes which were suppose a to be great de licasies, followed
by a fish which was really quite good. It was worth the price of admission to
see Groeger worry with the Chinese steward about what every thing was before
he would eat it.
All the time I knew that he would have given a lot for some
nice "pigs knuckles and kraut" but the poor fellow went the route like a good
sport. Today I asked him if he wanted another Chinese dinner tonight and he
just looked sort of pale and said he'd be willing to wait until we got to
China where we might not be able to ge t anything else.
I played deck tennis today in the middle of a snow storm. It was the
first exercise I have had on board.
